'''Cheryl Savageau''' (born April 14, 1950) is a poet of [[Abenaki]] descent.  She writes often about Native American people and places in [[New England]], where she has lived much of her life, as well as about working-class people, and [[feminist]] and [[queer]] issues.

Savageau was born in central Massachusetts. She is a graduate of [[Clark University]] and a facilitator at [[University of Massachusetts, Boston]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Osher Lifelong Learning Institute|url=http://www.umb.edu/olli/facilitators/cheryl_savageau|publisher=University of Massachusetts Boston|accessdate=16 March 2013}}</ref>

Savageau's awards include fellowships from the [[National Endowment for the Arts]], residencies at the [[MacDowell Colony]], and a Pulitzer Prize nomination for her second book, ''Dirt Road Home.''<ref>{{cite web|title=Faculty and Staff: Cheryl Savageau|url=http://www.umb.edu/olli/facilitators/cheryl_savageau|work=Osher Lifelong Learning Institute|publisher=University of Massachusetts-Boston|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref>   
Her work appeared in AGNI.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cheryl Savageau|url=http://www.bu.edu/agni/authors/C/Cheryl-Savageau.html|work=6/2010|publisher=AGNI|accessdate=16 March 2013}}</ref> 
Also a visual artist, she has exhibited her quilts,<ref>{{cite web|title=Cheryl Savageau|url=http://neculture.org/exhibit1/savageau.html|work="We're Still Here": Contemporary Indigenous New England Artists|publisher=University of New Hampshire|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref> paintings and other works<ref>{{cite web|title=Cheryl Savageau|url=http://neculture.org/invisible_visible/c_savageau.html|work="Invisible/Visible": Emerging Contemporary New England Native American Art|publisher=University of New Hampshire|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref>  at the Abbe Museum in Bar Harbor, the [[University of New Hampshire]],  and elsewhere.

==Publications==
;Poetry
*''Home Country''. Farmington, ME: Alice James Books, 1992. ISBN 9780914086949
*''Dirt Road Home''. Willimantic, CT: Curbstone Press, 1995. ISBN 9781880684306
*''Mother/Land''. London: Salt Publishing, 2006. ISBN 9781844712694<ref>{{cite journal|title="All This / Is Abenaki Country": Cheryl Savageau<U+2019>s Poetic Awikhiganak|journal=Studies in American Indian Literatures|date=Fall 2010|volume=22|series=3|pages=1<U+2013>25|quote=Savageau<U+2019>s newest book, Mother/Land, appeared in 2006 in Salt Publishing<U+2019>s Earthworks series, edited by Janet McAdams; this will put her even more visibly in the company of such esteemed poets as Carter Revard, Diane Glancy, and Heid Erdrich. |url=http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/studies_in_american_indian_literatures/summary/v022/22.3.senier.html|accessdate=16 March 2013|doi=10.1353/ail.2010.0013}}</ref>

;Children's books
*''Muskrat Will Be Swimming''. Gardiner, ME: Northland Pub., 1996, ISBN 9780873586047; San Val, Incorporated, 2006 ISBN	9781417763931

